This is a known breaking change. In .NET 10, MAUI adopted **edge-to-edge** display on Android (matching Android 15's requirements), which means `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer shrinks the layout — it was deprecated in Android API 30.

**The fix:** Listen for IME (keyboard) window insets and adjust your layout's bottom padding/margin accordingly.

### 1. Keep `adjustResize` in your manifest

In `Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml`, ensure your activity has:

```xml
<activity
    ...
    android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize" />
```

### 2. Handle IME insets in `MainActivity.cs`

```csharp
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        if (Window?.DecorView is { } decorView)
        {
            ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(decorView, new ImeInsetsListener());
        }
    }

    private class ImeInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeVisible = insets.IsVisible(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var imeHeight = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime()).Bottom;
            var systemBars = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.SystemBars()).Bottom;

            // Apply the larger of IME or system bar insets as bottom padding
            var bottomPadding = imeVisible ? imeHeight : systemBars;
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottomPadding);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### 3. Your XAML (no special changes needed)

```xml
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" Command="{Binding SendCommand}" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

### Why this works

With edge-to-edge, your app draws behind system bars and the keyboard. The `WindowInsetsCompat` API tells you exactly how many pixels the keyboard occupies. By applying that as bottom padding on the decor view, the entire layout (including your input bar) shifts up above the keyboard — replicating the old `Resize` behavior.

> **iOS note:** iOS already handles this correctly via `UIScrollView` keyboard avoidance; no changes needed there.
